f haemagglutination (HA). Include in your answer why HA is useful for quantifying the antigen concentration of flu vaccines and why the temperature of the assay particularly important?',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(44,1,'You are making plates to assay the cleavage of bacterial cell walls by lysozyme. This involves preparation of agar in buffer, to which bacterial suspension will be added after autoclaving. You need to prepare 500ml of buffered agar, with the following composition:\r\r<p>\r20mM Tris buffer, pH7.5,<br>\r100mM NaCl, <br>\r1.5% (w/v) agar</br>\r</p>\r\rYou have a stock of 1M Tris buffer, pH7.5. How much of this will you need, to make a final 500ml of the solution above?',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(45,1,'How much solid NaCl (molecular weight 58.44) will you need for a final 500ml of the solution above?',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(46,1,'How much agar will you need for a final 500ml of the solution above?',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(47,1,'The buffered agar is autoclaved in 18ml aliquots. You have a suspension of bacteria to add to the agar which needs to be diluted 1 in 10 in the final solution. How much do you add to each 18ml aliquot?',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(48,1,'Name the two major subsets of T cells and the characteristic surface marker for each of them.',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(49,1,'Desribe their roles in no more than two sentences each.',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(50,1,'Describe the origin of antigen peptides (e.g. cytoplasmic, etc) displayed on MHC class I and MHC class II molecules.',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(51,1,'To which subset of T cells does each class display antigens?',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(52,1,'To which subset of T cells does each class display antigens?',NULL,'',NULL,'2016-11-04 16:22:23'),(53,1,'Describe the primary components of innate and adaptive immunity in response to a viral infection. How do these components confer protection agai