effects can prophage have on their host cell?',NULL,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:22:48','2016-10-30 15:22:48'),(69,3,'Which statement relating to innate immunity is FALSE?',214,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:23:45','2016-11-04 23:02:03'),(70,3,'The activation of naïve T cells occurs in:',216,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:26:04','2016-11-04 23:02:03'),(71,3,'Which statement about the B cell receptor (BCR) is FALSE?',225,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:26:49','2016-11-04 23:02:03'),(72,3,'Which of the following mechanisms is not a way in which antibodies act?',230,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:27:50','2016-11-05 01:03:15'),(73,3,'Allergies are predominantly a result of:',233,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:28:36','2016-11-04 23:02:03'),(74,3,'Antibody class switching is:',237,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:29:25','2016-11-04 23:02:03'),(75,3,'Which statement about neutrophils is FALSE?',241,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:30:15','2016-11-04 23:02:03'),(76,3,'Upon activation by a PAMP, dendritic cells in peripheral tissues:',249,NULL,'2016-10-30 15:31:51','2016-11-04 23:02:03'),(78,3,'Describe the mechanism of conservative transposition and explain how it work at the molecular level: (2 marks)',NULL,'The transposable element is excised from one location and becomes re-inserted at a second location. The copy number of a conservative transposon therefore remains one.','2016-10-30 15:43:45','2016-11-02 19:26:50'),(79,3,'Describe the mechanism of replicative transposition and explain how it work at the molecular level: (2 marks)',NULL,'A new copy of the transposon is produced during transposition and inserted at another location. Thus one copy of the transposon remains at the original site and another copy is found at a new site.','2016-10-30 15:43:51','2016-11-02 19:26:50'),(80,3,'Describe FOUR (4) mechanisms by which bacterial virulence factors can promote host colonization. (4 marks)',NULL,'Adhesins - promote attachment to host cells (e.g. BabA and SabA in H. Pylori)<br>\r\nImmunoglobulin proteases - some bacteria are able to break down host immunoglobulins to depress the immune response to infection (e.g. S. Pyrogenes)<br>\r\nDestructive Enzymes - Bacteria are able to produce enzymes to destroy host tissues, (e.g. Hemolysins in S. Aureus cause lysis of red blood cells)<br>\r\nEndotoxins - Bacteria can produce toxins which trigger intense inflammation, (e.g. LPS on gram negative bacteria)<br>\r\n','2016-10-30 15:44:16','2016-11-02 19:26:50'),(81,3,'Some virulent strains of Helicobacter pylori produce the CagA protein. Explain: <br> <p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">How is CagA produced and secreted by H. pylori? (2 marks)</p>',NULL,'The cagA pathogenicity island encodes for a Type IV secretion system.<br>\r\nThe type IV secretion system is like a molecular syringe.<br>\r\nThe CagA protein is injected into host cells via this mechanism.','2016-10-30 15:46:31','2016-11-02 22:45:10'),(82,3,'Some virulent strains of Helicobacter pylori produce the CagA protein. Explain: <br> <p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">What effect does CagA secretion have on the host cell? (2 marks)</p>',NULL,'CagA secretion causes the host cell to produce pro-inflammatory cytokines and also disrupts gap junctions.','2016-10-30 15:46:37','2016-11-02 19:26:50'),(83,4,'The evolutionary relationship between two organisms is their _______',252,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:01:56','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(84,4,'True or False. From the tree of life we discovered that the archaea are more closely related to the bacteria than they are to the eukarya.',256,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:02:43','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(85,4,'Mitochondria cluster close to the ___________ in the phylogenetic tree of life.',259,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:02:52','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(86,4,'If organism A used H<sub>2</sub>S as an electron donor and Fe<sup>3+</sup> as an electron acceptor (at pH of 7) and organism B used glucose as an electron donor and O<sub>2</sub> as an electron acceptor, which organism can probably produce more energy?',262,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:01','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(87,4,'True or False. Compared to other molecules in the electron transport chain NADH is the most negative E<sup>&ohbar;</sup> and the greatest capactiy to donate electrons.',264,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:08','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(88,4,'If you have a cell that uses glucose for carbon and energy and lives at 95&deg;C, what terms can you correctly apply to this organism?',269,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:15','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(89,4,'True or False. Oxygenic photosynthesis is when photosynthesis is performed but no oxygen is produced.',271,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:27','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(90,4,'In addition to chlorophyll molecules, phototrophic organisms also require accessory molecules known as ____________',272,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:35','2016-11-02 12:11:12'),(91,4,'True or False, Inorganic nitrogen compounds are oxidized aerobically by certain bacteria in the process known as nitrification.',277,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:44','2016-11-02 12:11:13'),(92,4,'How is new organic matter synthesized in nature?',280,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:50','2016-11-02 12:11:13'),(93,4,'What is the name of this process NO<sub>3</sub><sup>-</sup> &rarr; N<sub>2</sub>?',284,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:03:59','2016-11-02 12:11:13'),(94,4,'What is the largest source of methane release into the atmosphere?',287,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:04:07','2016-11-02 12:11:13'),(95,4,'Where do we find evidence for early microbial life?',291,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:04:15','2016-11-02 12:11:13'),(96,4,'The first cell was likely',298,NULL,'2016-11-02 12:04:23','2016-11-02 12:11:13'),(97,5,'A bacterial culture grows exponentially from 1 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/ml to 6.4 x 10<sup>7</sup> cells in 2 hours. What is the number of generations, the generation time and the mean growth rate constant of this bacterial culture?<br><br>N<sub>0</sub> = 1 x 10<sup>6</sup>, N = 6.4 x 10<sup>7</sup>, t = 2 hr',NULL,'Number of Generations\r\nn = (log N - log N<sub>0</sub>) / log2\r\nn = (log(6.4 x 10<sup>7</sup>) - log(1 x 10<sup>6</sup>)) / log2\r\nn = (7.806 - 6) / 0.301\r\nn = 6\r\n\r\nGeneration Time\r\ng = t/n\r\ng = 2/6 hrs\r\ng = 0.33 hrs\r\n\r\nMean Growth Rate\r\nk = 1/g hr<sup>-1</sup>\r\nk = 3 hr<sup>-1</sup>','2016-11-02 12:48:03','2016-11-02 13:03:50'),(99,5,'Distinguish between specific growth rate and generation time?',NULL,'','2016-11-02 13:31:01','2016-11-02 14:40:01'),(100,5,'Why do cells enter stationary phase?',NULL,'','2016-11-02 13:31:08','2016-11-02 14:40:01'),(101,5,'Under what circumstances would a lag phase not occur?',NULL,'','2016-11-02 13:31:19','2016-11-02 14:40:01'),(102,5,'Draw a typical growth curve for bacteria in batch culture and label the different phases of growth. In addition describe how synthesis of an antibiotic would vary during the growth curve.',NULL,'','2016-11-02 13:32:20','2016-11-02 14:40:01'),(103,5,'If in 8 hours an exponentially growing cell population increases from 2x10<sup>5</sup> cells/ml to 3.2x10<sup>6</sup> cells/ml, calculate n, g, and k.',NULL,'','2016-11-02 13:33:29','2016-11-02 14:40:01'),(104,5,'Which is a good way to test the \"excess acid hypothesis\"',301,NULL,'2016-11-02 14:38:13','2016-11-02 14:40:01'),(105,3,'Compare and contrast enveloped and naked viruses in terms of their assembly within infected cells.',NULL,'','2016-11-02 21:14:12','2016-11-02 22:45:10'),(106,3,'Compare and contrast enveloped and naked viruses in terms of their release from infected cells',NULL,'enveloped viruses bud through the infected cell\'s membrane becoming coated in membrane.<br><br>\r\n\r\nnaked viruses lyse the infected cell and are released en-masse into the extracellular fluid.','2016-11-02 21:14:17','2016-11-04 23:21:02'),(107,3,'Name TWO (2) different bacterial Pathogen-Associated Molecular Patterns (PAMPs), and the cellular receptors which recognise them. (2 marks)',NULL,'Bacterial Lipoproteins - recognised by TLR1<br>\r\nPeptidoglycan - recognised by TLR2\r\n\r\n','2016-11-02 21:15:51','2016-11-04 23:21:02'),(108,3,'What is the important effect that Pathogen-Associated Molecular Patterns (PAMPs) have on dendritic cell surface molecules which helps to restrict T cell activation to situations of infection? (2 marks)',NULL,'detection of a PAMP, by Pathogen Recognition Receptors (PRR), tell the dendritic cell to up-regulate B7, this is a secondary signal that a T cell requires in conjunction with antigen expressed on the DC\'s MHC molecule in order for the T cell to become activated. If the secondary signal is absent, the T cell will become desensitised to that antigen and will not react to it in the future. This is important for peripheral tolerance.','2016-11-02 21:15:56','2016-11-04 23:21:02'),(109,3,'In the lectures we discussed the brewing of Nøgne ø Dark Horizon. Using a description of the brewing process, indicate when the Pasteur and/or Crabtree effect was likely taking place. Justify your answer.',NULL,'The Pasteur effect is when the yeast produces ethanol under anaerobic conditions. The crabtree effect takes place at the beginning of the brewing process when oxygen is high as well as after the infusion of 100% oxygen that kickstarts the brewing process after the sugar syrup is added.','2016-11-02 21:16:12','2016-11-04 23:21:02'),(110,3,'With reference to influenza viruses, briefly explain the phenomenon of haemagglutination (HA). Include in your answer why HA is useful for quantifying the antigen concentration of flu vaccines and why the temperature of the assay is particularly important?',NULL,'Haemagglutination is the process where virus or bacteria binds to red blood cells and keeps them in suspension and prevents them from settling out of solution and forming a pellet at the bottom of the well. It is useful to quickly determine the concentration of a virus stock (30 min.)','2016-11-02 21:16:21','2016-11-05 00:01:50'),(111,3,'Describe the primary components of innate and adaptive immunity in response to a viral infection. How do these components confer protection against viral infections?',NULL,'Innate defences occur within the first hours of infection, Pathogen Recognition Receptors detect PAMPS, and trigger the release of cytokines and chemokine, these cause inflammation, permeability of vessels and attraction of immune cells. Infected DC\'s will travel to draining lymph nodes and present antigen on MHC Class I cells to CD8 T-Cells in conjunction with a co-stimulatory signal (B7). Matching T-Cells will be activated to  convert to CTL\'s, these can directly kill infected cells.','2016-11-02 21:16:31','2016-11-05 00:01:50'),(112,3,'You are making plates to assay the cleavage of bacterial cell walls by lysozyme. This involves preparation of agar in buffer, to which bacterial suspension will be added after autoclaving. You need to prepare 500 mL of buffered agar, with the following composition:<br> 20 mM Tris buffer, pH = 7.5, 100 mM NaCl, 1.5% (w/v) agar<br> You have a stock of 1 M Tris buffer, pH = 7.5. How much of this will you need to make a final 500 mL of the solution above?',NULL,'V<sub>2</sub> = 0.500 L<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 0.020 mol/L<br>\r\nC<sub>1</sub> = 1 mol/L<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (C<sub>2</sub> x V<sub>2</sub>)/C<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (0.020 mol/L x 0.500 L)/1 mol/L<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = 0.01 L<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>Tris</sub> = 10 mL</b>','2016-11-02 21:17:32','2016-11-05 00:01:50'),(113,3,'How much solid NaCl (molecular weight 58.44) will you need for a final 500 mL of the solution above?',NULL,'1.5% (w/v) = 1.5 g / 100 mL<br>\r\nM<sub>NaCl</sub> = 1.5 g / 100 mL x 500 mL<br>\r\n<b>M<sub>NaCl</sub> = 7.5 g</b>\r\n','2016-11-02 21:17:46','2016-11-05 00:01:50'),(114,3,'How much agar will you need for a final 500 mL of the solution above?',NULL,'V<sub>agar</sub> = 500 mL - 10 mL<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>agar</sub> = 490 mL</b>','2016-11-02 21:17:53','2016-11-05 00:01:50'),(115,3,'The buffered agar is autoclaved in 18 mL aliquots. You have a suspension of bacteria to add to the agar which needs to be diluted 1 in 10 in the final solution. How much do you add to each 18 mL aliquot? (2 marks)',NULL,'C<sub>1</sub> = 10 mol/mL<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 1 mol/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = χ mL<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = 18 mL + χ mL<br>\r\nC<sub>1</sub>V<sub>1</sub> = C<sub>2</sub>V<sub>2</sub><br>\r\n10 mol/mL × χ mL = 1 mol/mL x (18 mL + χ mL)<br>\r\n(10 mol/mL × χ mL / 1 mol/mL) = 18 mL + χ mL<br> \r\n10χ mL = 18 mL + χ mL<br>\r\n10χ mL - χ mL = 18 mL<br>\r\n9χ mL = 18 mL<br>\r\n<b>χ = 2mL</b><br>\r\n\r\n','2016-11-02 21:18:04','2016-11-05 00:46:14'),(116,3,'Name the TWO (2) major subsets of T cells and the characteristic surface marker for each of them. (1 mark)',NULL,'CD4 T Cells and CD8 T Cells<br>\r\nCD 4 T Cells have TCR\'s that recognise antigen presented on MHC Class II molecules.<br>\r\nCD8 T Cells have TCR\'s that recognise antigen presented on MHC Class I molecules<br>','2016-11-02 21:18:21','2016-11-05 00:46:14'),(117,3,'Describe their roles in no more than TWO (2) sentences each. (1 mark)',NULL,'CD4 T cells help combat intracellular pathogens, by either becoming Th1 or Th2 cells. Th1 cells activate macrophages to phagocytose and ingest pathogens, whereas Th2 cells stimulate B cells to make antibodies.<br>\r\n\r\nCD8 T cells help combat intercellular pathogens by becoming Cytotoxic T Lymphocytes, and directly killing infected cells.','2016-11-02 21:18:31','2016-11-05 00:46:14'),(118,3,'Describe the origin of antigen peptides (e.g. cytoplasmic, etc.) displayed on MHC class I and MHC class II molecules. (2 marks)',NULL,'MHC Class I molecules display antigens peptides from inside the cell (cytoplasmic)\r\nMHC Class II Molecules display antigen peptides from outside the cell or from phagosomes.','2016-11-02 21:18:41','2016-11-05 00:46:14'),(119,3,'To which subset of T cells does each class display antigens? (1 mark)',NULL,'MHC Class I displays antigens to CD8 T Cells\r\nMHC Class II displays antigens to CD4 T Cells','2016-11-02 21:18:50','2016-11-05 00:46:14'),(120,3,'The following question is based on phagocytosis: What is opsinisation and how does it enhance the immune response to bacteria?',NULL,'Opsonisation is the enhancement of phagocytic activity by coating a pathogen in antibody or serum complement proteins, the Fc portion of the antibody binds to the Fc receptor on the phagocyte and triggers the ingestion of the pathogen.','2016-11-02 21:19:16','2016-11-05 00:55:24'),(121,3,'Describe THREE (3) mechanisms that bacteria could utilise to resist killing by phagocytic cells. (3 marks)',NULL,'Inhibition of phagocyte chemotaxis\r\nInhibition of engulfment\r\nInhibition of fusion of phagocytic lysosomes','2016-11-02 21:19:32','2016-11-05 01:03:15'),(122,6,'List the major difference between viruses and bacteria',NULL,'Bacteria can be visualised under light microscopy - Viruses cannot<br>\r\nBacteria replicate independently - viruses cannot, they replicate within a host cell and exist as an inert macromolecule outside a living host.<br>\r\nBacteria grow and replication - viruses only replicate (assemble)<br>\r\nBacteria have genome that encodes for energy requirements for the cell, viruses do not encode for energy of high potential they rely on their host cell for energy input.<br>','2016-11-02 21:50:18','2016-11-04 21:07:50'),(123,6,'How do viruses acquire an envelope? How are enveloped viruses ifferent from naked viruses? Give examples of each!',NULL,'Enveloped viruses acquire their envelope when they \"bud\" from the plasma membrane of the infected cell. <i>e.g. Influenza</i><br><br>\r\n\r\nNaked viruses do not have an envelope because they lyse the infected cell and release all the virus progeny. <i>e.g. Poliovirus</i><br><br>','2016-11-02 21:50:51','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(124,6,'What are the different structural components of a virus?',NULL,'Nucleic acid genome, Capsid (together these are called the nucleocapsid), Lipid envelope (optional).<br>\r\nMany viruses will also have included proteins and glycoproteins.','2016-11-02 21:51:03','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(125,6,'List the major symmetries that viruses utilise and give an example for each.',NULL,'Helical - Tobacco Mosaic Virus (TMV)\r\nIcosahedral - Poliovirus\r\nComplex - T4 Phage','2016-11-02 21:51:36','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(126,6,'What factors determine the structure of a virus',NULL,'Size and coding capacity of the genome<br>\r\n- genome size has to fit within nucleocapsid\r\n- number of structural proteins avaliable<br>\r\n- most economic nucleocapsid symmetry. <br><br>\r\n\r\nFunctional requirements<br>\r\n- protection of bacteria from environment<br>\r\n- mode of cell attachment and penetration<br>\r\n- mode of replication<br>\r\n- mode of virion assembly and release','2016-11-02 21:51:44','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(127,6,'Viruses are thought to have made important contributions to the evolution of cellular life - discuss this statement including theories on the origins of viruses',NULL,'Recent discoveries of giant viruses containing genes that are used for some complext tasks like making proteins, repairing and replicating DNA. Have led some scientists to postulate that giant viruses could have come before cellular life and may have provided the raw material for the development of cellular life.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIt is undisputed that retroviruses have played a large role in the evolutionary development of placental mammals as the remnants of an ancient retrovirus is responsible for the ability of Humans and other placental mammals to grow a placenta necessary for reproduction.','2016-11-02 21:52:24','2016-11-04 17:45:01'),(128,6,'Briefly describe the replication strategy of a + sense RNA virus, Give an example',NULL,'Poliovirus is an example of a + sense RNA viruses.<br>\r\nPolio is a naked virus and does not have an envelope, it attaches to a cellular receptor and forms a pore in the membrane and it\'s RNA enters the cytoplasm and acts as mRNA which can be immediately translated into a single polyprotein by host ribosomes.  The polyprotein is then cleaved into individual proteins. Now viral proteins are available to copy the + sense RNA into a negative strand, the negative strand is then used to make more copies of the full length + strand RNA ready for packaging.','2016-11-02 23:12:58','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(129,6,'Briefly describe the replication strategy of a - sense RNA virus, Give an example',NULL,'An example of a - sense RNA virus is the influenza virus.<br>\r\nThe Influenza virion haemagglutinin protein binds to the sialic acid receptor on its target cell, the target cell endocytoses the particle and in the endosome the pH change triggers the haemagglutinin to fuse the viral envelope with the endosomal membrane releasing the particle into the cytosol. The particle then travels to the nucleus where it\'s - sense RNA is transcribed into mRNA and then exported to the cytosol where they are translated into proteins. The virus then needs to replicate it\'s genome, it makes a full length + strand copy of the genome which is then used as a template to make copies of the - strand. This must occur for all 8 segments of the genome.','2016-11-02 23:13:06','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(130,6,'The genomes of <u>most</u> DNA viruses replicate in the cytoplasm while <u>most</u> RNA viruses replicate in the nucleus.',305,NULL,'2016-11-02 23:14:49','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(131,6,'List six (6) different type of viral genomes (e.g. Double stranded DNA)',NULL,'Double stranded DNA<br>\r\nSingle stranded DNA<br>\r\nDouble stranded RNA<br>\r\nSingle stranded + sense RNA<br>\r\nSingle stranded - sense RNA<br>\r\nSingle stranded + sense RNA with DNA intermediate (retroviruses)<br>\r\nDouble stranded DNA with RNA intermediate','2016-11-02 23:15:22','2016-11-04 22:37:59'),(132,6,'List the basic stages of virus infection of the host cell (i.e. attachment etc.)',NULL,'Attachment\r\nEntry / Penetration\r\nUncoating\r\nTranscription and Translation\r\nAssembly and Release\r\n\r\n','2016-11-02 23:15:43','2016-11-04 22:56:22'),(133,6,'List the 2 types of antiviral drugs (ie list two different modes of action) that are used to treat influenza infections - for each give an example of a drug (chemical or trade name)',NULL,'<br>Neuraminidase inhibitor (Oseltamivir) - inhibits the neuraminidase that cleaves off the sialic acid to release new particles from the cell, new virus particles remain stuck to the cell and can\'t disseminate<br><br>\r\n\r\nM2 Channel Inhibitor (Amantadine) - inhibits the action of the M2 ion channel, preventing the acidification of the influenza particle required for fusion of the endosomal membrane with the viral envelope.','2016-11-02 23:16:23','2016-11-04 22:57:07'),(134,6,' What events in viral infection can cause disease symptoms? Give examples!',NULL,'Damage to cells due to viral replication\r\n- loss of function\r\n- cell death (necrosis/apoptosis)\r\n- transformation (ie. tumours)\r\nDamage due to host immune response to infection\r\n- fever\r\n- inflammation','2016-11-02 23:29:34','2016-11-06 18:04:58'),(135,6,'How do host factors modify the outcome of viral pathogenesis? Give examples!',NULL,'Host factors such as: \r\nGenetics - e.g. having a mutation where CCR5 is shortened, you have reduced susceptilibity to HIV\r\nAge - e.g. Glandular fever, chickepox, measles, denge fever and ross river all mild in children\r\nMetabolic state - i.e. malnutrition, deficiency and pregnancy\r\nAltered immune response - i.e. impaired or enhanced\r\n','2016-11-02 23:29:51','2016-11-06 18:04:58'),(136,6,'Describe the different types of viral infection in terms of the timing and appearance of disease symptoms and clearance of the virus from the body - give examples?',NULL,'Acute: e.g. flu, cold, yellow fever\r\nChronic/persistent: e.g. HIV, HCV\r\nLatent/Re-occuring: e.g. herpes complex','2016-11-02 23:30:18','2016-11-06 20:08:19'),(137,6,'Different viruses may infect similar epithelial cell surfaces, however their pathogenesis, in terms of the organs/tissues in the host that are affected, may vary greatly. Explain with examples!',NULL,'Some viruses produce a spreading infection at site of entry and then shed directly to exterior (e.g. influenza). However, other viruses produce a polarised infection of epithelial cells and spread - the targeting of viral budding to apical or basal surfaces of polarised cells may define subsequent spread (e.g. herpes complex)','2016-11-02 23:31:03','2016-11-06 20:08:19'),(138,6,'Under what conditions could bacteriophage be useful for treating bacterial diseases in humans? How would this work? What type of phage and replication strategy would this involve? How would phage be selected and what problems may be encountered?',NULL,'Bacteriophages are more useful where biofilm is covered by a polysacchride layer which antibiotics cannot penetrate. They are more specific than common drugs and also harmless to beneficial bacteria. Thay can replicate in viv and a smaller dosage is required. It could be a solution to multi-drug resistance. Bacteriophages can be used to express foreign genes, diagnostic antigens and synthetic antibodies -> e.g Filamentous SS DNA phage M13','2016-11-02 23:39:07','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(139,6,'List the various strategies to express foreign genes in eukaryotic cells using viruses. Also list the various applications these strategies can be used for.',NULL,'','2016-11-02 23:39:51','2016-11-04 17:45:02'),(140,6,'How can viruses be used to achieve gene silencing? How can gene silencing be used for cell biology research',NULL,'A short RNA sequence complementary to target mRNA + cellular enzymes: forms a RNA-Induced Silencing Complex (RISC). RISC recognises target mRNA and leads cleavage -> therefore: target mRNA degradation','2016-11-02 23:40:12','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(141,6,'Briefly describe the lytic and lysogenic cycles bacteriophage',NULL,'The viral DNA encased in a temperate virus attached to the host cell -> injection of viral DNA into host cell (temperate virus detaches):\r\nLYTIC CYCLE:\r\nViral DNA replicates within host cell-> coat proteins are synthesised and assembled -> LYSIS takes places and replicated temperate viruses leave host cell (due to osmotic pressure?) \r\nLYSOGENIC CYCLE:\r\nAfter injection of viral DNA into host cell -> viral DNA is integrated into the host DNA cell (PROPHAGE) -> Lysogenised cell -> cell division ->Induction into replicating staged of LYTIC CYCLE','2016-11-02 23:46:02','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(142,6,'What are prophage? How can they affect their bacterial host?',NULL,'A prophage is a viral DNA integrated into host cell DNA \r\nThey can:\r\n- prevent phage replicating \r\n- can provide immunity to other phage infections\r\n- expression of prophage genes may also effect the virulence of bacteria - medical significance: e.g. diphtheria, botulism and scarlet fever  - caused by bacteria carrying prophage genes that allow the bacteria to make toxins\r\n\r\n','2016-11-02 23:46:12','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(143,6,'Do bacteriophage have any medical significance? Explain!',NULL,'Use in health and hygiene:\r\n- phage typing of bacterial pathogens (highly host specific)\r\n- as preservatives in food\r\n- as antibacterial agents \r\n---e.g. PhagoBioDerm used to treat S.aureus wound\r\n---ADVANTAGES:\r\nvery specific\r\nintelligent drug\r\nevolve\r\nactive against bacteria resistant to antibiotics\r\ncan be genetically modified\r\n---DISADVANTAGES:\r\nfew recognised studies\r\nbacteria can become resistant\r\nrelatively large->affect accessibility\r\nneed to know exact strain to treat\r\nmay transfer toxins between bacteria\r\nmore difficult to antibiotics','2016-11-02 23:46:25','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(144,6,'Some plant viruses have multipartite genomes. Briefly explain!',NULL,'Multipartite means viruses with SEGMENTED GENOMES in DIFFERENTED GENOMIC SECTIONS in DIFFERENT VIRUS PARTICLES\r\n- plant cell must be infected with viruses containing each of the genomic sections in order to have replication/expression\r\n\r\nOn the other hand: animal viruses = segmented genomes - all genomic segments in single virus particle (e.g. influenza)','2016-11-02 23:46:49','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(145,6,'How do viruses infect plants and spread from cell to cell and establish systemic infection within the plant?',NULL,'Plants have RIGID CELL WALLS and cannot be entered by ENDOCYTOSIS or FUSION => must enter by mechanical means: vector (nematode worms and insects) or shearing/cutting.\r\nAfter vector introduces virus into the plant - the virus must bypass the rigid cell wall barrier to spread from cell to cell. Plants have a thin trans-wall which connects cells: PLASMODESMATA\r\nPlants viruses code for movement protein which facilitated movement of virus through plasmodesmata channel\r\n\r\n','2016-11-02 23:47:08','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(146,6,'How can bacteriophage and plant viruses be useful',NULL,'Virus and fungi can help wild plants adapt to extreme conditions\r\nBacteriophages are useful in food preservation and medical treatment options','2016-11-02 23:47:17','2016-11-06 20:36:13'),(147,7,'Make 200 mL of 0.5 M KCl. The MW of KCl is 74.55. How much KCl should you weigh out?',NULL,'0.5 mol/L x 0.200 L = 0.100 mol<br>\r\n0.100 mol x 74.55 g/mol = 7.455 g<br><br>\r\n<b>Mass<sub>KCl</sub> = 7.455 g</b>','2016-11-03 21:13:03','2016-11-04 19:52:58'),(148,7,'Make 100 mL of 600 mM urea. The MW of urea is 60.06. How much urea should you weigh out?',NULL,'0.600 mol/L x 0.100 L = 0.06 mol<br>\r\n0.06 mol x 60.06 g/mol = 3.6036 g<br><br>\r\n<b>Mass<sub>urea</sub> = 3.6036 g</b>','2016-11-03 21:15:28','2016-11-04 19:58:49'),(149,7,'The molecular weight of glucose is 180.16. What is the molar concentration of a 5%(w/v) solution?',NULL,'Concentration: 5% (w/v) = 5g/100ml<br>\r\nMol. Weight: 180.16 g/mol<br><br>\r\n\r\n5g/0.100 L x 1/180.16 mol/g<br>\r\n0.278 mol/L<br>\r\n<b>C<sub>glucose</sub> = 278 mM</b>','2016-11-03 21:15:33','2016-11-04 19:52:58'),(150,7,'You need to make 500 mL of 50 mM Tris buffer, pH 7.4, 5mM EDTA. The molecular weight of Tris base is 121.1. You have a 250mM stock of EDTA. How much Tris base and EDTA would you measure out?<br>\n(Note, if making this, these would have to be dissolved in approximately 450ml of water, and then the pH adjusted using HCl, since you have the base form of the buffer, before making up the volume to 500ml).',NULL,'Tris Base<br>\r\n0.050 mol/L x 0.500 L = 0.025 mol<br>\r\n121.1 g/mol x 0.025 mol = 3.0275 g<br>\r\n<b>M<sub>Tris</sub> = 3.0275 g</b><br><br>\r\n\r\nEDTA<br>\r\nC<sub>1</sub> = 0.250 mol/L<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = 0.500 L<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 0.005 mol/L<br><br>\r\n\r\nC<sub>1</sub>V<sub>1</sub>=C<sub>2</sub>V<sub>2</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = C<sub>2</sub>V<sub>2</sub>/C<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (0.005 mol/L x 0.500 L) / 0.250 mol/L<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>EDTA</sub> = 10 mL</b>\r\n\r\n','2016-11-03 21:15:41','2016-11-04 19:52:58'),(151,7,'Agar is added to PYE broth at 1.5%(w/v). How much agar do you need to add to each 500 mL bottle before autoclaving?',NULL,'Concentration = 1.5g per 100mL<br>\r\n1.5g per 100mL x 5 = <b>7.5g per 500mL</b>','2016-11-03 21:15:47','2016-11-04 19:52:58'),(152,7,'King medium A contains 1.4 g/L anhydrous MgCl2. What is its molarity in this solution? The molecular weight of anhydrous MgCl2 is 95.21.',NULL,'1.4 g/L ÷ 95.21 g/mol = 0.0147 mol/L<br>\r\n14.7 mM','2016-11-03 21:15:52','2016-11-04 19:52:58'),(153,7,'How would you make up 40 mL of 10%(w/v) ferric chloride? The molecular weight of ferric chloride is 162.2',NULL,'Concentration: 10 g / 0.100 L = 100 g/L<br>\r\n100 g/L x 0.040 L = 4 g<br><br>\r\n<b>Dissolve 4g of ferric choloride in final volume of 40mL of water</b>','2016-11-03 21:15:56','2016-11-04 20:10:57'),(154,7,'You have counted your purified macrophage cells and they are 2.4 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells per mL. You need to prepare 4 mL of cells in growth medium at 1 x 10<sup>5</sup> cells per ml. What volume of cells and what volume of medium do you mix together?',NULL,'C<sub>1</sub> = 2.4 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 1 x 10<sup>5</sup> cells/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = 4 mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (V<sub>2</sub> x C<sub>2</sub>)/C<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (4 mL x 1 x 10<sup>5</sup> cells/mL)/2.4 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>cells</sub> = 0.167 mL</b><br>\r\nV<sub>medium</sub> = 4 mL - 0.167 mL<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>medium</sub> = 3.833 mL</b><br>\r\n','2016-11-03 21:17:02','2016-11-04 18:59:58'),(155,7,'You have 10x stock of PBS buffer which you use for washing ELISA plates after dilution to the 1x working concentration. How would you make up 500 mL of the working concentration?',NULL,'Take 50mL of 10x PBS buffer and dilute with 450mL water','2016-11-03 21:17:06','2016-11-04 19:07:16'),(156,7,'Your stock of sodium nitrite for the nitrite assay is stored at 250mM. You want to make up 100 μM solution, diluted in medium. How would you make up 50 mL of this?',NULL,'C<sub>1</sub> = 250 mM<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 100 µM = 0.100 mM<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = 50 mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (V<sub>2</sub> x C<sub>2</sub>)/C<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (50 mL x 0.100 mM)/250 mM<br>\r\nV<sub>cells</sub> = 0.020 mL<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>Sodium Nitrate</sub> = 20 µL</b><br>\r\n<b>V<sub>medium</sub> = 49.98 mL</b><br>','2016-11-03 21:17:10','2016-11-04 19:14:45'),(157,7,'You usually use an antibody at 2 μg/mL. The new stock which has arrived has a concentration of 0.52 mg/mL. How would you make up 5 mL of antibody at 2 μg/mL in PBS buffer?',NULL,'C<sub>1</sub> 0.52 mg/mL = 520 µg/mL<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 2 µg/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = 5 mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (V<sub>2</sub> x C<sub>2</sub>)/C<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (5 mL x 2 µg/mL)/520 µg/mL<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>antibody</sub> = 19.23 µL</b><br>\r\nV<sub>PBS</sub> = 5mL - 0.01923 mL<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>PBS</sub> = 4.98 mL</b><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2016-11-03 21:17:14','2016-11-04 20:10:57'),(158,7,'You have 2 mL of cells which are at 5 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL. If you want to dilute them in growth medium to 2 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells per mL, how much medium should you add to them?',NULL,'C<sub>1</sub> = 5 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = 2 mL<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub>2 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = (C<sub>1</sub> x V<sub>1</sub>)/C<sub>2</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = ( 5 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL x 2 mL)/2 x 10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>final</sub> = 5 mL<br>\r\nV<sub>medium</sub> = 5mL - 2mL<br>\r\n<b>V<sub>medium</sub> = 3mL</b><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n','2016-11-03 21:17:18','2016-11-04 19:24:21'),(159,7,'You have a precious, highly potent novel antibiotic, and you have a stock of 1 mg/mL. You want to make tubes of 10 mL of growth medium, with the antibiotic at a final concentration of 1 ng/mL. Can you add this directly from the stock that you have?? What volume would you have to measure of the 1mg/ml stock? What concentration of stock would you need, such that you could add 10 μL into a final volume of 10 mL, and have the 1 ng/mL final concentration? How would you make this new stock solution from the existing 1mg/ml stock?',NULL,'C<sub>1</sub> = 1 mg/mL = 1 x 10<sup>-3</sup> g/mL<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 1 ng/mL = 1 x 10<sup>-9</sup> g/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = 10 mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (C<sub>2</sub> x V<sub>2</sub>)/C<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = (1 x 10<sup>-9</sup> g/mL x 10 mL)/1 x 10<sup>-3</sup> g/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = 0.000001 mL = 0.01 µL<br><br>\r\n\r\nCan you add this directly from the stock you have?<br>\r\n<b>No, You cannot add this directly from the stock that you have, the volume is too small</b><br><br>\r\nWhat volume would you have to measure of the 1 mg/mL stock?<br>\r\n<b>0.01 µL</b><br><br>\r\n\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = 10 x 10<sup>-3</sup> mL<br>\r\nV<sub>2</sub> = 10 mL<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 1 x 10<sup>-9</sup> g/mL<br>\r\nC<sub>1</sub> = (C<sub>2</sub> x V<sub>2</sub>)/V<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nC<sub>1</sub> = (1 x 10<sup>-9</sup> g/mL x 10 mL)/10 x 10<sup>-3</sup> mL<br>\r\nC<sub>1</sub> = 1 x 10<sup>-6</sup> g/mL<br><br>\r\n\r\nWhat concentration of stock would you need, such that you could add 10 μL into a final volume of 10 mL, and have the 1 ng/mL final concentration?<br>\r\n<b>1 µg/mL</b><br><br>\r\n\r\nHow would you make this new stock solution from the existing 1mg/ml stock?<br>\r\n<b>Make a 1000:1 dilution, take 1 µL of the stock and add to 0.999 mL of water.</b>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2016-11-03 21:17:21','2016-11-04 19:52:58'),(160,7,'You want to use LPS to study effects on macrophage TLR4. You have macrophages plated in wells containing 0.49 mL of medium. You want to add LPS at a final concentration in the well, of 10 ng/mL. What concentration of stock LPS will you need to have, so that you can add 10 μL to each well and get the final concentration of 10 ng/mL?',NULL,'V<sub>2</sub> = 0.500 mL<br>\r\nC<sub>2</sub> = 10 ng/mL<br>\r\nV<sub>1</sub> = 0.01 mL<br>\r\n\r\nC<sub>1</sub> = (C<sub>2</sub> x V<sub>2</sub>)/V<sub>1</sub><br>\r\nC<sub>1</sub> = (10 ng/mL x 0.500 mL)/0.01 mL<br>\r\n<b>C<sub>LPS</sub> = 500 ng/mL</b><br>\r\n','2016-11-03 21:17:37','2016-11-04 19:48:06'),(161,8,'Flagella:',306,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:15:27','2016-11-05 21:26:32'),(162,8,'The structure that confers rigidity and protects the cell from osmotic lysis is the:',311,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:15:42','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(163,8,'Which of the following statements about phototrophic microorganisms is <b>FALSE</b>?',405,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:16:14','2016-11-06 01:01:26'),(164,8,'A microorganism uses carbon dioxide as a carbon source, hydrogen as an energy source (electron donor) and grows optimally at 75°C and pH=10. What terms can you apply to this organism?',324,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:17:04','2016-11-05 21:26:32'),(165,8,'Identification of the three domains of life, Bacteria, Archaea, and Eukarya, has come about primarily as a result of:',327,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:17:18','2016-11-05 21:26:32'),(166,8,'If in 15 hours an exponentially growing cell population increases from 1x10<sup>6</sup> cells/mL to 3.2x10<sup>7</sup> cells/mL, calculate n, g, and k:',330,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:17:30','2016-11-05 21:26:32'),(167,8,'Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a feature of an integron?',339,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:17:42','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(168,8,'Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a virulence factor produced by <i>Helicobacter pylori</i>?',344,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:17:53','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(169,8,'Which of the following statements best describes <i>Streptococcus pyogenes</i>?',345,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:18:05','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(170,8,'<i>Coccidioides immitis</i>:',354,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:18:14','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(171,8,'Lager is most commonly produced:',356,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:18:23','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(172,8,'The rabies virion is ___________, possesses a _____________ viral genome and a nucleocapsid that exhibits ____________________ symmetry.',363,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:18:34','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(173,8,'Viruses differ from all bacteria in that:',368,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:18:43','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(174,8,'Which of the following <b>BEST</b> represents a strategy to express a foreign protein in a eukaryotic cell?',374,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:19:38','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(175,8,'What effects can prophage have on their host cell?',NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:19:50','2016-11-05 17:19:50'),(176,8,'Which statement relating to innate immunity is <b>FALSE</b>?',383,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:20:00','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(177,8,'The activation of naïve T cells occurs in:',385,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:20:10','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(178,8,'Which statement about the B cell receptor (BCR) is <b>FALSE</b>?',394,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:20:18','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(179,8,'Antibody class switching is:',396,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:20:28','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(180,8,'Which of the following statements is <b>FALSE</b>? Well-recognised complications of tick bites in Australia include:',401,NULL,'2016-11-05 17:20:37','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(181,8,'List the steps required to conduct a Gram-stain and describe the appearance of the types of bacteria identified by this procedure.',NULL,'Prepare smear on glass slide and fix by passing under the flame a few times.<br>\r\nCover smear with crystal violet and leave for 1 minute<br>\r\nWash with water<br>\r\nCover smear with iodine and leave for 1 minute<br>\r\nWash with water<br>\r\nHold slide at 45°ree; angle and apply ethanol to top edge of smear until no more colour washes out (10-15 seconds)<br>\r\nWash with water<br>\r\nCounterstain with safranin and leave for 1 minute<br>\r\nwash with water, blot dry<br><br>\r\n\r\nGram positive bacteria will appear dark purple and gram negative will appear pink.','2016-11-05 17:20:51','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(182,8,'Explain why nitrate (NO<sub>3</sub><sup>2-</sup>) is the preferred electron acceptor in anaerobic respiration.',NULL,'NO<sub>3</sub><sup>2-</sup> has a very high reduction potential, almost as high as oxygen, but in an anaerobic environment, oxygen is not available.','2016-11-05 17:20:59','2016-11-05 21:43:48'),(183,8,'What are the two hypotheses for the endosymbiotic origin of Eukaryotes? Which is the preferred hypothesis for the formation of the Eukaryotic lineage, and why?',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:21:10','2016-11-05 20:58:46'),(184,8,'Describe the mechanism of conservative transposition and explain how it work at the molecular level:',NULL,'The transposable element is excised from one location and becomes re-inserted at a second location. The copy number of a conservative transposon therefore remains one.','2016-11-05 17:21:55','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(185,8,'Describe the mechanism of replicative transposition and explain how it works at the molecular level:',NULL,'A new copy of the transposon is produced during transposition and inserted at another location. Thus one copy of the transposon remains at the original site and another copy is found at a new site.','2016-11-05 17:22:19','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(186,8,'Describe FOUR (4) mechanisms by which bacterial virulence factors can promote host colonization.',NULL,'Adhere to host cells (pili; adhesins)<br>\r\nInvade host cells (invasins; proteins that allow penetration of host cells)<br>\r\nContact host cells (motility and flagella)<br>\r\nResist phagocytosis and complement (capsule)<br>\r\nCompete for nutrients (siderophores)','2016-11-05 17:22:28','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(187,8,'Some virulent strains of <i>Helicobacter pylori</i> produce the CagA protein. How is CagA produced and secreted by <i>H. pylori</i>?',NULL,'The cagA pathogenicity island encodes for a Type IV secretion system.<br>\r\nThe type IV secretion system is like a molecular syringe.<br>\r\nThe CagA protein is injected into host cells via this mechanism.','2016-11-05 17:22:54','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(188,8,'Some virulent strains of <i>Helicobacter pylori</i> produce the CagA protein. What effect does CagA secretion have on the host cell?',NULL,'CagA secretion causes the host cell to produce pro-inflammatory cytokines and also disrupts gap junctions.','2016-11-05 17:23:13','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(189,8,'In the lectures we discussed the brewing of Nøgne ø Dark Horizon. Using a description of the brewing process, indicate when the Pasteur and/or Crabtree effect was likely taking place. Justify your answer.',NULL,'The Pasteur effect is when the yeast produces ethanol under anaerobic conditions. The crabtree effect takes place at the beginning of the brewing process when oxygen is high as well as after the infusion of 100% oxygen that kickstarts the brewing process after the sugar syrup is added.','2016-11-05 17:23:23','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(190,8,'Describe FOUR (4) key features of the <i>Sacchromyces pastorianus</i> genome',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:23:34','2016-11-05 20:58:46'),(191,8,'Compare and contrast the assembly of enveloped and naked viruses within infected cells.',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:24:11','2016-11-05 20:58:46'),(192,8,'Compare and contrast the release of enveloped and naked viruses from infected cells.',NULL,'enveloped viruses bud through the infected cell\'s membrane becoming coated in membrane.<br><br>\r\n\r\nnaked viruses lyse the infected cell and are released en-masse into the extracellular fluid.','2016-11-05 17:24:27','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(193,8,'Describe the primary components of innate and adaptive immunity in response to a viral infection. How do these components confer protection against viral infections?',NULL,'Innate defences occur within the first hours of infection, Pathogen Recognition Receptors detect PAMPS, and trigger the release of cytokines and chemokine, these cause inflammation, permeability of vessels and attraction of immune cells. Infected DC\'s will travel to draining lymph nodes and present antigen on MHC Class I cells to CD8 T-Cells in conjunction with a co-stimulatory signal (B7). Matching T-Cells will be activated to  convert to CTL\'s, these can directly kill infected cells.','2016-11-05 17:24:36','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(194,8,'Explain how a naked DNA vaccine induces a protective immune response to a viral antigen (Use a diagram if you wish).',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:24:48','2016-11-05 20:58:46'),(195,8,'Name TWO (2) different bacterial Pathogen-Associated Molecular Patterns (PAMPs), and the cellular receptors which recognise them.',NULL,'Bacterial Lipoproteins - recognised by TLR1<br>\r\nPeptidoglycan - recognised by TLR2\r\n','2016-11-05 17:25:33','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(196,8,'What is the important effect that Pathogen-Associated Molecular Patterns (PAMPs) have on dendritic cell surface molecules which helps to restrict T cell activation to situations of infection?',NULL,'detection of a PAMP, by Pathogen Recognition Receptors (PRR), tell the dendritic cell to up-regulate B7, this is a secondary signal that a T cell requires in conjunction with antigen expressed on the DC\'s MHC molecule in order for the T cell to become activated. If the secondary signal is absent, the T cell will become desensitised to that antigen and will not react to it in the future. This is important for peripheral tolerance.','2016-11-05 17:26:03','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(197,8,'Name the TWO (2) major subsets of T cells and the characteristic surface marker for each of them.',NULL,'CD4 T Cells and CD8 T Cells<br>\r\nCD 4 T Cells have TCR\'s that recognise antigen presented on MHC Class II molecules.<br>\r\nCD8 T Cells have TCR\'s that recognise antigen presented on MHC Class I molecules<br>','2016-11-05 17:26:15','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(198,8,'Describe the roles of T Cells in no more than TWO (2) sentences each. (1 mark)',NULL,'Th2 cells. Th1 cells activate macrophages to phagocytose and ingest pathogens, whereas Th2 cells stimulate B cells to make antibodies.<br>\r\n\r\nCD8 T cells help combat intercellular pathogens by becoming Cytotoxic T Lymphocytes, and directly killing infected cells.','2016-11-05 17:26:53','2016-11-06 00:19:11'),(199,8,'You are making plates to assay the cleavage of bacterial cell walls by lysozyme. This involves preparation of agar in buffer, to which bacterial suspension will be added after autoclaving. You need to prepare 500 mL of buffered agar, with the following composition:<br><br>20 mM Tris buffer, pH = 7.5,<br>100 mM NaCl, 1.5% (w/v) agar<br><br>You have a stock of 1 M Tris buffer, pH = 7.5. How much of this will you need to make a final 500 mL of the solution above?',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:28:22','2016-11-05 20:58:47'),(200,8,'How much solid NaCl (molecular weight 58.44) will you need for a final 500 mL of the solution above?',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:28:32','2016-11-05 20:58:47'),(201,8,'How much agar will you need for a final 500 mL of the solution above?',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:28:42','2016-11-05 20:58:47'),(202,8,'The buffered agar is autoclaved in 18 mL aliquots. You have a suspension of bacteria to add to the agar which needs to be diluted 1 in 10 in the final solution. How much do you add to each 18 mL aliquot?',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:28:51','2016-11-05 20:58:47'),(203,8,'Give the scientific and common names for 2 species of lice that infect humans.',NULL,'','2016-11-05 17:29:05','2016-11-05 20:58:47');
