LL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:58'),(33,1,154,NULL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:58'),(34,1,155,NULL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:59'),(35,1,156,NULL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:59'),(36,1,157,NULL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:59'),(37,1,158,NULL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:59'),(38,1,159,NULL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:59'),(39,1,160,NULL,'?','2016-11-03 21:25:10','2016-11-04 18:09:59'),(40,4,83,252,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(41,4,84,256,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(42,4,85,259,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(43,4,86,262,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(44,4,87,264,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(45,4,88,269,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(46,4,89,271,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(47,4,90,276,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(48,4,91,277,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(49,4,92,280,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(50,4,93,284,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(51,4,94,287,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(52,4,95,291,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(53,4,96,298,NULL,'2016-11-04 01:55:42','2016-11-04 01:55:42'),(54,4,122,NULL,'Bacteria can be visualised under light microscopy - Viruses cannot\r\nBacteria replicate independently - viruses cannot, they replicate within a host cell and exists as an inert macromolecule outside a living host. \r\nBacteria grow and replication - viruses only replicate (assemble)\r\nBacteria have genome that encodes for energy requirements for the cell - viruses do not encode for energy (cannot produce ATP), they rely on their host cell for energy input. \r\nBacteria can contain both nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) - viruses can only have one or the other','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(55,4,123,NULL,' Acquired from a host cell membrane when virus “buds”\r\n(plasma membrane) or passes through a membrane-bound\r\norganelle (such as the nucleus, golgi etc)','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(56,4,124,NULL,'- viral genomes can be either RNA or DNA (not both)\r\n- viral genome surrounded by protein capsid to protect genome\r\n- can be enveloped or naked (naked virus is more tougher than enveloped)\r\n- ','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(57,4,125,NULL,'- icosahedral eg Paramyoxovirus (measles)\r\n- helical eg Togavirus (Ross river)','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(58,4,126,NULL,'Size and coding capacity of the genome\r\n- genome size has to fit within nucleocapside\r\n- number of structural proteins avaliable\r\n- most economic nucleocapsid symmetry. \r\n\r\nFunctional requirements\r\n- protection of bacteria from environment\r\n- mode of cell attachment and penetration\r\n- mode of replication\r\n- mode of virion assembly and release','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(59,4,127,NULL,'Recent discoveries of giant viruses containing genes that are used for some complex tasks like making proteins, repairing and replicating DNA. Have led some scientists to postulate that giant viruses could have come before cellular life and may have provided the raw material for the development of cellular life.\r\n\r\nIt is undisputed that retroviruses have played a large role in the evolutionary development of placental mammals as the remnants of an ancient retrovirus is responsible for the ability of Humans and other placental mammals to grow a placenta necessary for reproduction.','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(60,4,128,NULL,'plus sense RNA viruses are able to use their own genome directly as mRNA. Poliovirus can use this replication strategy. ','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(61,4,129,NULL,'minus sense RNA are able to use their own polymerase . An example is rabies virus ','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(62,4,130,304,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:48'),(63,4,131,NULL,'DS DNA\r\nSS DNA\r\nDS RNA\r\nSS +RNA\r\nSS - RNA\r\nSS RNA (replicated with DNA intermediate)\r\nDS DNA (replicates with RNA intermediate)','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-04 18:05:02'),(64,4,132,NULL,'- attachment and entry\r\n- penetration\r\n- initiation of replication\r\n- synthesis of viral genome and replication \r\n- maturation and release of viruses\r\n','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-05 02:34:15'),(65,4,133,NULL,'Drug 1: Amantadine treats influenza A strains by targeting the matrix proteins. the chemical type is tricyclic amine\r\n\r\nDrug 2: Relenza treats influenza A and B strains by targeting the neuraminidase inhibitor. the chemical type is neuraminic acid mimetic. ','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-05 02:34:15'),(66,4,134,NULL,'1) Damage to cells due to virus replication\r\neg. Necrosis - causes cell death by rupture of cell during virus release\r\n\r\n2) Damage to cells due to immune response\r\neg. ','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-05 16:45:27'),(67,4,135,NULL,'Genetics and age\r\n\r\nGenetics eg. If an individual carries a mutation in one of the cell receptors for HIV (CD4 and CCR5), then this individual may be more suspectible to this infection as compared with someone who expresses these receptor proteins. \r\n\r\nAge. Some viral infections can be worsened with age. \r\neg. the flu is more severe in the elderly \r\neg. Chicken pox and measles are childhood diseases and are more common in adolescents. ','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-05 16:45:27'),(68,4,136,NULL,'1. Acute - the rapid development of symptoms but usually results in the complete recorvery of the individual (or sometimes death). Overall, viruses are cleared from the body\r\n\r\n2. Chronic - long, slow infections eg. HIV\r\nthese infections could show constant symptoms throughout life time, no symptoms, or symptoms that occur later on in life. Overall, the virus is not cleared from the body. \r\n\r\n3. Recurrent or latent - the re-occurance of symptoms from a virus which has been dorminant, The virus is present in the body and does not go away., it is however, dormant. A specific trigger (eg. chemical ) can re activate this virus and its symptoms occur','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-05 16:45:27'),(69,4,137,NULL,'Localized and systemic spread\r\n\r\nLocalized: viruses that infect and cause infection in the same site of infection. They multiply at site of entry. eg. respiratory infections (influenza), gastrointestinal infections and dermatological infections. A surface infection - where viruses fail to spread within deeper tissues eg influenza virus in respiratory epithelial\r\n\r\nSystematic - invasion of deeper tissues eg. herpes complex virus','2016-11-04 18:05:02','2016-11-05 16:45:27'),(70,4,138,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(71,4,139,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(72,4,140,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(73,4,141,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(74,4,142,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(75,4,143,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(76,4,144,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(77,4,145,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(78,4,146,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-04 18:05:03','2016-11-04 18:05:03'),(79,1,122,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 21:10:30'),(80,1,123,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 21:10:30'),(81,1,124,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 21:10:30'),(82,1,125,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 21:10:30'),(83,1,126,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 21:10:30'),(84,1,127,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 21:10:30'),(85,1,128,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 21:10:30'),(86,1,129,NULL,'?','2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 22:38:47'),(87,1,130,305,NULL,'2016-11-04 21:10:30','2016-11-04 22:59:24'),(88,1,131,