the preferred hypothesis as it is supported by the fact the eukaryotics share similarities with both archeae and prokaryotics (similar translation and transcription machinery to archeae, similar membrane structure to prokaryotics).','2016-11-05 23:31:58','2016-11-05 23:31:58'),(621,15,184,NULL,'Conservative transposition: Insertion sequences recognized by transposase, transposition complex is formed. Excision event occurs, resulting in the movement of the DNA between the two IS sequences. Recognition of target site by transposase and insertion of transposon into target DNA region.\r\n','2016-11-05 23:31:58','2016-11-05 23:31:58'),(622,15,185,NULL,'Fusion of replicative transposon with target DNA. Replication of transposon. Cointegration of transposons. Resolution of donor and recipient. End up with two transposons.','2016-11-05 23:31:58','2016-11-05 23:31:58'),(623,15,186,NULL,'1. coloization of a niche in host (e.g. by adhesins, flagella)\r\n2. immunoevasion of host immune system (e.g. capsules in pseudomonas aeurginosa (cystic fibrosis), streptoccous pyrogenes )\r\n3. immunosuppression (e.g. immunoglobulin proteases in streptococcous pyrogenes)\r\n4. entry into and out of host cell (if it lives intracellularly) (e.g. salmonella triggering engulfment by epithelial cells).\r\nbbbbbbonus\r\n5. stealing nutrients from the host. e.g. siderophores (iron scavenging molecule)','2016-11-05 23:31:58','2016-11-05 23:31:58'),(624,15,187,NULL,'CagA is encoded by CagA pathogenicity island. This set of genes encodes for both CagA and the type IV secretory system. The type IV secretory system secretes CagA  which affects the epithelial lining of the host cell.','2016-11-05 23:31:58','2016-11-05 23:31:58'),(625,15,188,NULL,'CagA results in disrupted gap junctions between the epithelial cell lining. This results in penetraction of H.pylori and the gastric juices further into the host tissue, potentially leading to increased cases of gastric ulcers.','2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(626,15,189,NULL,'Pasteur effect - > Presence of oxygen inhibits the fermentation process. High O2 -> less fermentation and therefore alcohol production.\r\nCrabtree effect -> High concentration of glucose leads to preference of anaerobic respiration over aerobic respiration. High glucose -> high alcohol\r\n \r\nBrewing of Dark Horizon involved pitching of yeast into the wort followed by addition of high sugar syrup after fermentation started to slow, aeration with 100% O2, and finally switching to wine yeast once beer yeast died. Initial addition of the yeast to the wort would have resulted in predominately the crab tree effect taking place as the wort has high glucose concentrations. As the glucose levels went down and fermentation slowed glucose syrup was added again resulting in increased grabtree effect. As the sugar from the syrup decreased aeration occured, increasing the pasteur effect, resulting in increased cell growth and division.  Beer yeast were switched for wine yeast as beer yeast typically die at around ~12% alcohol while wine yeast can survive higher concentrations.','2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(627,15,190,NULL,'Small genome size (for a eukaryote). Short life cycle, undergoes sexual and asexual division with diploid and haploid phases (haploid phases easily amenable with mutations). Many genes are homologous to those found in other eukaryotic cells. Fairly easy to invoke heterogeneous protein production. Has codon bias.','2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(628,15,191,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(629,15,192,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(630,15,193,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(631,15,194,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(632,15,195,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(633,15,196,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:31:59'),(634,15,197,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-05 23:31:59','2016-11-05 23:3