ree energy level between the donor and acceptor is likely still high so the reaction will still work. The reason it\'s preferred in anaerobic respiration is (duh) cause there is no oxygen present. ','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(748,2,183,NULL,'Archaea (hydrogen consumer) eats bacteria (hydrogen producer). They fall in love and live happily ever after. This formation essentially starts the eukaryotes on the phylogenetic tree. This is the preferred theory as archaea have similar internal structures to eukaryotes but eukaryotes have a similar membrane structure to bacteria. \r\n\r\nThe other, not preffered hypothesis is that eukaryotes ate bacteria. (same hydrogen based principles as above). ','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(749,2,184,NULL,'IS sequence is where the transposase recognises and cuts at both ends, transposon is sandwiched in between the two IS sequences.\r\nexcision event occurs after complex formation. \r\nSequence is then inserted into host genome at the target site.\r\n\r\n','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(750,2,185,NULL,'Transposon is copied between IS sequences by machinery. \r\nit twists around onto itself forming a complex\r\nthe duplicate pops off and gets inserted at target site.','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(751,2,186,NULL,'colonisation of the host cell\r\n - ahdesins binding to epithelial cells\r\nimmuno evasion\r\nimmunosupression\r\nentry in and out of the cell','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(752,2,187,NULL,'pathogenicity island gene sequence code for CagA and the type IV secretory system.\r\n\r\nCagA type IV secretory system injects the CagA virulence factor into the cell\r\n\r\nthe exact mechanisms are unknown.','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(753,2,188,NULL,'gap junctions get all messed up by cytotoxin release (widened).\r\n\r\n','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(754,2,189,NULL,'sugars are extracted from grain during steeping (amylase breaks down starch). \r\n wort is boiled with hops to add bitterness. \r\nwort is cooled to fermentation temp.\r\nyeast is pitched and crabtree effect comes into play due to high glucose, primary metabolite ethanol is produced from glucose by growing yeast.\r\nwort has glucose syrup added, high glucose = crabtree\r\nwort is aerated with 100% oxygen = pastuer\r\nyeast dies close to 12% ABV,  neither effect.\r\nwine yeast pitched, crabtree in effect whilst primary metabolite production takes the beer from 12-16% abv. \r\n','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(755,2,190,NULL,'small, easy to manipulate.\r\n\r\nhas haploid state, amendable to mutation.\r\n\r\nfast life cycle\r\n\r\nasexual reproduction','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(756,2,191,NULL,'penetration: apparatus attaches to cell, viral genome is injected into cell along with capsid.\r\n\r\ndisassembly, capsid disconnects from viral dna, replication occurs.\r\n\r\nre-assembly after replication and synthesis. \r\n\r\nsame for enveloped, but penetration is usually done through fusion of envelope and host membrane. gets envelope back through secretion (budding).\r\n','2016-11-06 02:19:21','2016-11-06 02:19:21'),(757,2,192,NULL,'Lysing the cell (naked)\r\n - so much replication the cell eventually busts a nut into the cytoplasm. releasing it\'s spawn. \r\n\r\nBudding out of the cell. (enveloped)\r\n-  as replication occurs, the assembled bits just leave the cell (taking some membrane)','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(758,2,193,NULL,'Innate:\r\n - complement (neutralising), dendritic (transport to adaptive), natural killer (killing, pow pow).\r\n\r\nAdaptive\r\n - T cell activation (recognises MHC-I with CD8 TCR)\r\n  - Mature T cells effector function: travel to site of infection, release apoptotic factors that kill virally infected cells. \r\n','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(759,2,194,NULL,'avirulent virus thingi is bound up in a virus like particle capsule. this capsule is injected into host, immune system responds by developing T memory cells (in conjunction with everything else).\r\n\r\nthose memory cells are then ready to bang when the real virus comes around.','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(760,2,195,NULL,'foreign dna fragments\r\n - toll-like receptors\r\n\r\nbacterial flagellin\r\n - toll-like receptors\r\n\r\npattern recognition receptors  are also a thing that exist.\r\n','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(761,2,196,NULL,'they signal dendritic cells to present the antigen on their surface (by moving the MHC receptors from inside to outside) T cells recognise these and activate, proliferate, mature and move to the site of infection ','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(762,2,197,NULL,'cytotoxic T cells, surface marker: CD8\r\n\r\nhelper T cells: surface marker: CD4','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(763,2,198,NULL,'Cytotoxic t cells role are to recognise MHC1 receptors and interact / bind using CD8 surface proteins. this leads them to mature and either migrate to site of infection for cytokine release, or stay in the lymph node as memory cells.\r\n\r\nhelper t cells, these recognise MHCII receptors on the dendritic cells and mature into either TH1 or TH2 cells. Th1 signal and upregulate innate immune response via IFgamma. TH2 release two cytokines IL-4 and IL-5 to the B cells.','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(764,2,199,NULL,'25ml','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(765,2,200,NULL,'2.922g','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(766,2,201,NULL,'7.5g','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(767,2,202,NULL,'1.8mL','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(768,2,203,NULL,'EAD\r\n\r\npubic lice\r\npthirus pubis\r\nhead lice\r\npediculus humanus capitis','2016-11-06 02:19:22','2016-11-06 02:19:22'),(769,27,1,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-06 11:47:09','2016-11-06 11:47:09'),(770,27,2,NULL,NULL,'2016-11-06 11:47:09','2016-11-06 11:47:09'),(771,27,3,NU