H2 consuming archaea (the symbiont) and a H2 producing bacteria. This is supported by the similarity of lipid content in eukaryotes and bacteria, and the transcriptional machinery of archaea and eukaryotes.','2016-11-06 14:46:32','2016-11-06 14:46:32'),(1007,10,184,NULL,'Conservative transposition excises a transposable element or IS element from one segment of the genome, and reincorporates in another location. The insertion of the sequence results in the formation of direct repeats on either side of the sequence. The transposition is a process carried out by the enzyme transposase, and the incorporation into the genome is sealed by DNA polymerase and ligase.','2016-11-06 14:46:32','2016-11-06 14:46:32'),(1008,10,185,NULL,'Replicative transposition is where a transposon is copied from one location into another. The transposon is unzipped, and one strand of DNA is integrated into the target site, and DNA polymerase is used to make the second strand of DNA. The two transposons are then crossed over, swapping half of the transposon between the sites. The sites are then cleaved, leaving two identical copies of the transposon at each site. ','2016-11-06 14:46:32','2016-11-06 14:46:32'),(1009,10,186,NULL,'1) adherance to host cells to avoid being physically removed (humoral immunity) \r\n2) motility to be able to contact host cells \r\n3) evasion of host immune system\r\n4) Invasion into host cells by invasins (increase penetration of cell membranes)','2016-11-06 14:46:32','2016-11-06 14:46:32'),(1010,10,187,NULL,'CagA is translated with a cluster of genes that code for the CagA pathogenicity island. This island forms a type IV secretion system and effectively acts as a syringe to inject CagA into host cells ','2016-11-06 14:46:32','2016-11-06 14:46:32'),(1011,10,188,NULL,'CagA promotes the host cell to release pro-inflammatory cytokines.','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1012,10,189,NULL,'The beer is brewed using aerobic and anaerobic metabolism of saccharomyces pastorianus. During anaerobic respiration (or fermentation), S. pastorianus produces ethanol as a primary metabolite from the sugar provided, described by the Pasteur effect. In aerobic respiration where there are high concentrations of glucose available, S. pastorianus also produces ethanol, most likely as a way to poison other nutrient competing bacteria. This combination of anaerobic and aerobic adds body and flavour to the beer. ','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1013,10,190,NULL,'1) small genome \r\n2) can be haploid or diploid \r\n3)homologous to some eukaryotic genes\r\n4) Can reproduce sexually \r\n','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1014,10,191,NULL,'Enveloped viruses hijack the host machinery to produce surface proteins and to replicate their genome. Once the genome is replicated, the sequence is transported to the cell membrane, where it combines with the newly translated surface proteins and exocytoses from the cell, taking with it some host membrane. Naked viruses create the proteins needed for viral assembly (e.g. capsomeres) and are assembled within the cell, until the cell cannot fit any more virus particles inside, and is lysed. ','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1015,10,192,NULL,'Enveloped viruses bud off from the host cell, slowly degrading the membrane, whereas naked viruses break the membrane by internal pressure. ','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1016,10,193,NULL,'The innate immune system sends macrophages to phagocytose the virus (and any other foreign particles) and degrade them internally. The adaptive immune system creates antibodies to specifically target the viral particles and infected cells, recruiting phagocytes to the site of infection. ','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1017,10,194,NULL,'The DNA is injected and integrated into chromosomes. The gene of interest (antigen) is then transcribed and translated and exocytosed, allowing the host to mount an immune response based on this protein. This is beneficial as the DNA is non-pathogenic','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1018,10,195,NULL,'TLR4 recognises lipopolysaccharides \r\nTLR9 recognises bacterial and viral DNA','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1019,10,196,NULL,'They supply a costimulatory signal, communicating to T cells that the antigen they have perceived is pathogenic. ','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1020,10,197,NULL,'Cytotoxic T lymphocytes: CD8 receptors\r\nT helper cells: CD4 receptors','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1021,10,198,NULL,'T cells help B cells to create antibodies and recruit macrophages, or can directly kill infected/infectious cells. ','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1022,10,199,NULL,'...','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1023,10,200,NULL,'....','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1024,10,201,NULL,'...','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1025,10,202,NULL,'....','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1026,10,203,NULL,'Pediculus capitus\r\npediculus humanis','2016-11-06 14:46:33','2016-11-06 14:46:33'),(1027,2,83,252,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1028,2,84,256,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1029,2,85,259,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1030,2,86,262,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1031,2,87,264,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1032,2,88,269,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1033,2,89,271,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1034,2,90,272,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1035,2,91,277,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1036,2,92,280,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1037,2,93,284,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1038,2,94,287,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1039,2,95,291,NULL,'2016-11-06 14:50:58','2016-11-06 14:50:58'),(1040,2,96,2